# History

## Foundation of Christianity

##### Has its roots in [[Unsorted/Paganism\|Paganism]]

- Many small cults were formed around [[Unsorted/Prophet\|prophetic]] individuals ; wandering mystics
	- Apollonius of Tyana
		- Wandering vagrant
		- Activities
			- Says very wise things
			- Performs miracles
				- Plague-curing
				- Raised the dead
				- [[Unsorted/Prophet\|Prophesizing]]
					- Predicted that the [[Unsorted/The Roman Empire\|Roman]] emperor would be assassinated
			- Receives food and resources for his services
		- Gets kicked out of a city because they feared him
		- Allegedly had a vision when the [[Unsorted/The Roman Empire\|Roman emperor]] actually was assassinated
		- Considered to be equal or superior to [[Unsorted/Messiah\|Jesus]]
			- Wasn't executed, for one
	- Also [[Unsorted/Messiah\|Jesus]]
- Other cults were formed around pagan gods
	- Known as ***"Mystery Religions"***
	- Common features
		- Have an intense initiation, like a fraternity
			- Little is known about them today, because they swear to never reveal the secrets of their cults
				- Were open about their affiliation with the cults
				- But not about the details
		- Large communal meals
	- Became more individual-focused over time
	- Occurred when institutions were breaking down
		- And seeking new forms of connection with others
		- Comparable to the modern world, and the formation of fraternities
	- People could belong to many different ones, no limit
	- Examples
		- [[Unsorted/Ancient Greeks#^Eleusenian-Mysteries\|Ancient Greeks#^Eleusenian-Mysteries]]
		- Dionysus
			- AKA Bacchus
			- The god of *wild nature*
				- Non-civilization, irrationality, impulse
				- In the modern world is known as the god of wine
			- Rituals
				- Baccanalia
					- Women running into the hills naked
					- Abandoning workday mindset
					- Doing magic
					- Drinking wine
					- Nursing wild animals
					- Orgies
					- Frenzy of the hunt
						- Said to chase wild animals
						- And rip them apart with their bare hands
			- Multiple [[Unsorted/The Roman Empire\|Roman emperors]] were affiliated with the cult of Dionysus
		- Cybele / Magna Mater
			- Pronounced "Sibyl," but that's another word for Roman oracles
			- Other mythological figure, Attis
				- Propositioned by Cybele, but he refused
				- So he drove him insane
					- Made to castrate himself
			- Priests
				- Were castrated, done willingly by themselves
					- Seen as very strange in Rome
				- Did a ritual where they paraded into Rome
					- Followed a big black rock through the streets
					- Wore elaborate, effeminate gowns
					- Worked themselves up into a frenzy, and let it take them over
						- Pulled out knives, and started slashing themselves
							- Manifestation of their devotion to Sibyl
					- Some young Romans were into it and volunteered to be priests
						- But the Roman government tried to forbid Romans from joining
		- [[Isis\|Isis]]
			- Very influential
			- Often depicted with her son, Horus
		- Mithras
			- From [[Unsorted/Zoroastrianism\|Zoroastrianism]]
			- Agent of [[Unsorted/God (Monotheistic)\|Ahura Mazda]]
			- Taurobolium
				- Bull sacrifice ritual
					- Often performed in caves, resulted in much of their artifacts being preserved
				- Dig a bit pit with a metal grating over it
				- Initiates are rushed into the pit
				- Bull is sacrificed on top of the pit
					- Baptising the initiates in blood and entrails
				- Hallucinogens were likely involved
		- Many more cults were lost to time
- The idea of a [[Unsorted/Rewarding afterlife\|Rewarding afterlife]]
	- Emerged in the cults
	- A new concept, which was very comforting to people in comparison to Hellenism
- [[Unsorted/Messiah\|Jesus]]
	- [Was an actual person](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Historical_Jesus)
		- Likely baptized by John the Baptist
		- And crucified
			- Said to have descended into [[Class - Roots of Hell/Punishing afterlife\|Hell]] / [[Unsorted/Neutral afterlive\|Limbo]], creating an [[Earthquake\|Earthquake]] 
				- [[Unsorted/Hell Tropes#The Harrowing of Hell\|Freed worthy souls]], like old testament heroes, from [[Class - Roots of Hell/Punishing afterlife\|Hell]]
		- Likely born around 2-3 BC
			- Lived ~30 years
		- We only have about 
		- Spoke Aramaic
	- Came from Galilee, very rural area
		- A holy man, AKA Hasiid
	- Arrived in Jerusalem
		- Believed to be the Messiah, a preexisting prophecy
		- Smashed money-changers' tables 
	- Was imprisoned in Rome and crucified
		- Crucifiction is not a Roman practice, it's more Eastern
		- Makes a big statement
		- Represented by the lamb and fish before the crucufix
	- Made his followers very uncomfortable
		- The resurrection happened
			- central to the religion
	- His teachings were recorded by Paul
		- Spoke Greek
		- Never wrote about Jesus himself just his ideas
		- Taught ideas of social justice
			- "It is easier for a camel to fit through the eye of a needle than for a rich man to go to heaven"
				- The punishment of those who exploit others
			- The aid of those less fortunate
			- This threatened the Roman order
		- Lists those who will notbe allowed into the [[Unsorted/Rewarding afterlife\|Kingdom of God]]
			- Blasphemers
			- Unrepentant fornicators
			- Idolators
			- Adulterers
			- Homosexuals
			- Thieves
			- Drunkards
			- Slanderers
			- Swindlers
			- Sorcerers
			- The envious
		- Doesn't describe a [[Class - Roots of Hell/Punishing afterlife\|Punishing afterlife]] for these souls
			- Implied that [[Unsorted/Death\|Death]] itself is the punishment
- Early christianity doesn't try to be consistent
	- Tensions grew with [[Unsorted/Judiasm\|Jews]], who saw christians as confused jews
	- Hostility from [[Unsorted/The Roman Empire\|Rome]]
		- Rumored that they drank blood and ate bodies
			- May have actually happened, but likely misinterpretations of the wine/bread
		- Eventually granted religious freedom when christians became very numerous
		- In 380, became the official religion of [[Unsorted/The Roman Empire\|The Roman Empire]]
			- One thing which split the empire in half
	- Weren't sure which texts were canonical
		- And deciding which beliefs were heretical
- Eventually spread to the entirety of [[Unsorted/The Roman Empire\|Rome]], before the collapse, and became the official religion
- When [[Unsorted/The Roman Empire\|The Roman Empire]] collapsed
- ...the vehicle through which christianity spread was lost
	- Many thought this was 
- ...others blamed christianity for destroying the empire
	- Believed to be the wrath of the gods they dethroned
	- But likely due to the political instability that the spread of Christianity created
- ...St Augustine wrote "City of God"
	- Large anthology, >20 books
	- Tried to explain Rome as the "City of Man,"  and claimed that its collapse would not harm the Cityof God
	- In later books, wrote quite a lot about [[Class - Roots of Hell/Punishing afterlife\|Hell]]
	- His ideas later became the official positions of the church
		- Though there have always been conflicting ideas
- Eventually gave way to [[Unsorted/Medieval Christianity\|Medieval Christianity]]



## The Gospels
- "The Good News"
- 4 canonical Gospels
	- List
		- Mark
		- Matthew
		- Luke
		- John
	- Each is a different depiction of Jesus
	- About 20 non-canonical ones
		- Some fragmentary
		- The gnostic texts
		- Many lost, potentially more than 200
			- Funny one
				- When captured by Romans, he slipped away and someone else was crucified instead
				- That's how he was resurrecte
- Written long after [[Jesus\|Jesus]] lived
	- None are written by the disciples themselves
	- All written in Greek
		- Jesus spoke Aramaic
		- Which means all of the ideas in the Gospel were translated from his original words
			- Focused more on winning over followers than accurately depicting his ideaa
- Believed to be missing sources that directly influenced the gospels
	- Such as "Q," which strongly influenced both Matthew and Luke

- Suggested that the world would end very soon 

- Predated by The Letters of Paul
	- Still ~20y after Jesus' death

- **Mathew,** the gospel of:
	- Sinners: ^Matthew-sinners
		- Pharisees
		- Lawyers
		- Hypocrites
		- The greedy
	- Will be cast into "a furnace of fire"
		- "there shall be the wailing and gnashing of teeth"
- **Luke,** the gospel of:
	- The story of Dives and Lazarus (Not the main one)
		- Dives is a wealthy, extravagant man
		- Lazarus is a beggar, who laid in front of his door
		- Both of them die, and in [[Unsorted/Afterlives\|The Afterlife]] they are [[Unsorted/Afterlives\|Sorted]]
			- Dives goes to hell
				- Begs for several things from Abraham himself, but is refused
					- ...to let Lazarus bring him a drop of water
					- ...to be allowed to go back and warn his 5 brothers of hell
			- Lazarus ascends to the "[[Unsorted/Rewarding afterlife\|The Bosom of Abraham]]"
				- Definitely better than [[Class - Roots of Hell/Punishing afterlife\|Hell]], but vague
				- Cannot go to [[Unsorted/Rewarding afterlife\|Heaven]] unless baptized
					- Because Abraham existed pre-baptism, he wasn't baptised
					- [[Unsorted/Rewarding afterlife\|The Bosom of Abraham]] is a place imagined for them to go instead of [[Class - Roots of Hell/Punishing afterlife\|Hell]]
		- Source of [[Unsorted/Hell Tropes\|The Abominable Fancy]]
- **The Book of Revelation**
	- Very creative
		- Likely involved [[Psychadelics\|Psychadelics]]
	- Specifically created as a protest against [[Unsorted/The Roman Empire\|The Roman Empire]]
		- Particularly against emperor worship
	- Described the Christian [[Unsorted/The Apocalypse\|Apocalypse]]
		- Eschatology
		- Final cosmic battle between good and evil
			- Where [[Class - Roots of Hell/Ruler of Hell\|Satan]] will be defeated for good
		- Will begin when a scroll in [[Unsorted/God (Monotheistic)\|God]]'s right hand is opened
			- Can only be opened by a being known as both...
				- ...the Lion of Judah
				- ...the Lamb of God
					- 7 horns and 7 eyes
			- Closed by 7 (wax) seals
				- As each seal is cracked, different things happen:
					- 
					1.  Conquest, AKA Pestilence/disease
						- White horse, crown, there to conquer
						- Could be a good thing?
					2. War
						- Red horse, greatsword
					3. Famine
						- Black horse, holds scales
						- Rambles about trade
							- "A quart of wheat for a denarius, and three quarts of barley for a denarius; but do not damage the oil and wine"
							- Impossibly high prices for the time
								- The poor, unable to buy food
					4. Death
						- Ashen horse
						- Followed by [[Class - Roots of Hell/Ruler of Hell\|Hades (God)]]
						- Given authority over a quarter of the Earth to slaughter
						- [[Unsorted/Psychopomp\|Psychopomp]]
					5. hell?
						- Unworthy souls
							- ...whose names are not within "The Book of Life"
								- Suggests predestination
									- No clear reason why [[Unsorted/God (Monotheistic)\|God]] would create souls destined for this fate
									- Defeats the purpose of good deeds, which were favored by early christian writers 
							- ...will be flung into a lake of fire for a second death
					6. a
					7. a
	- Culminates in the Last Judgement
		- *Dies Irae*, day of wrath
		- The end of time
		- Jesus explains it in the gospel of Matthew
			- Sends the sheep to the right and the goats to the left
				- Says to left:
					- "Depart from me, ye cursed, into everlasting fire"
				- Says to right:
					- "And the righteous into life eternal"
			- No mention of the book of life
			- Has holes though
				- What happens between the death of individuals and judgement day
					- Do souls sleep?
				- Are there good/evil limbos?
				- Do the evil wait until judgement day before receiving punishment
					- And the good have to wait?




# Afterlife

- [[Class - Roots of Hell/Punishing afterlife\|Hell]]:
	- Little direct mention
	- Most mentions of it are translated from [[Unsorted/Ancient Greeks\|Greek]] words
		- Tartarus, Hades, and Gehenna
	- More details come from the gospel of Matthew
	- Later was expanded, along with the idea of Purgatory
		- Many ideas were codified in this time, such as:
			- The [[Unsorted/Sins\|7 deadly sins]]
- [[Unsorted/Neutral afterlive\|Limbo]]
	- A solution to prevent holy individuals who existed pre-baptism from going to [[Class - Roots of Hell/Punishing afterlife\|Hell]]
		- One existed for unbaptized babies
		- Another existed for old testament figures and cool pagans like Plato
		- Became the presiding idea in [[Modern Christianity\|Modern Christianity]]
			- In 2007 the Catholic church publically reconsidered the fate of dead infants
	- Only became a common idea long after [[Unsorted/Neutral afterlive\|Purgatory]] did
[[Unsorted/Neutral afterlive\|Purgatory]] (Middle christianity)
	- A place where the sinful-but-not-damned were cleansed of their sins so that they could go to heaven


# Figures
- [[Unsorted/God (Monotheistic)\|God]]
- [[Unsorted/Messiah\|Jesus]]
- [[Class - Roots of Hell/Ruler of Hell\|Lucifer]] / [[Class - Roots of Hell/Ruler of Hell\|Satan]]
	- The name [[Class - Roots of Hell/Ruler of Hell\|Lucifer]] originates from Isaiah, referencing the king of Babylon
		- A mortal man
			- Known as *morning star*, son of the dawn
		- Wanted to ascend above [[Unsorted/God (Monotheistic)\|God]]
			- Was cast down to the realm of the dead instead 
	- Originally the most beautiful and favored of all the angels - "The Fire-bearer"
		- There was a sort of insurrection in heaven
		- Tried to "sit in the seat of [[Unsorted/God (Monotheistic)\|God]]"
			- Maybe wanted to be more than / as powerful as [[Unsorted/God (Monotheistic)\|God]]
			- Was cast down to [[Class - Roots of Hell/Punishing afterlife\|Hell]] as punishment
		- Became ugly instead of beautiful, and changed name to [[Class - Roots of Hell/Ruler of Hell\|Satan]]
			- Means "adversary"
	- In the old testament
		- A henchman / messenger of [[Unsorted/God (Monotheistic)\|God]]
		- Mentioned as a source of bad...
			- ...events
				- Plague
				- Floods
			- ...and behaviors
				- Murder
				- Military misjudgement
		- Referred to as the destroyer
			- Once ridiculed by [[Unsorted/God (Monotheistic)\|God]] for punishing [[Unsorted/Judiasm\|Jerusalem]] too hard
	- In the new testament
		- Has more autonomy
			- And has authority over lesser demons
		- Is established as [[Unsorted/God (Monotheistic)\|God]]'s adversary
			- Will fight for evil in [[Unsorted/The Apocalypse\|The Apocalypse]]
			- Then burn in [[Class - Roots of Hell/Punishing afterlife\|Hell]], along with [[Unsorted/Death\|Death]], all sinners, and The Antichrist
	- Depictions
		- Originally depicted as blue instead of red
			- ![Pasted image 20221005153040.png](data:image/png;base64,)
		- Later depicted as large monsters, like sea dragons, and wyverns
			- And as the serpent in the garden of eden
- The Antichrist
	- Paul warned about false prophets
		- Early christians viewed all who preached false doctrines as an antichrist
		- Political and ideological opponents
			- Such as [[Unsorted/The Roman Empire\|Roman emperors]], preaching emperor worship
			- Simon Magnus of Samaria, a very influential [[Gnosticism\|Gnostic]]
			- [[The Pope\|The Pope]] during [[The Reformation\|The Reformation]], or the entire Papacy
				- Or Leaders of [[The Reformation\|The Reformation]] by Catholics
			- In modern times, basically every American president
